      <hedline>
        <hl1>Debating Tax-Cut Plans</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Margherita Davis letter on Bruce Bartlett's Aug 22 article on Vice Pres Al Gore's tax-cut plan questions Bartlett's call for letting taxpayers apportion their tax dollars</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The Cost of Keeping Gore's Promises'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 22), Bruce Bartlett argues the virtue of returning tax dollars to the taxpayer, for apportionment. My question: How much cancer research can (or will) an individual taxpayer purchase?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In ''The Cost of Keeping Gore's Promises'' (Op-Ed, Aug. 22), Bruce Bartlett argues the virtue of returning tax dollars to the taxpayer, for apportionment. My question: How much cancer research can (or will) an individual taxpayer purchase?</p>
        <p>Surely Mr. Bartlett must see that such investments by government will result in increased productivity and lesser health care costs in the future.</p>
        <p>MARGHERITA DAVIS  Hudson, N.Y., Aug. 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a registered nurse.</p>
      </block>
